abstract = {Summary This chapter provides information related to practical experiences and the latest developments and innovations of substation design using gas-insulated substation (GIS). It explains the effects and influences of insulation coordination and the reasons for studies are given. The chapter examines the health and safety impact of GIS and also explains very fast transient voltages and transient enclosure voltages for GIS. It describes the decomposition by-products of SF 6 and handling procedure. Most of the GIS equipment is shipped from the factory assembled and filled with positive SF 6 gas pressure or dry nitrogen. The GIS manufacturers follow the environmentally conscious design process, described in IEC 62430. Insulation coordination is the basic criteria for the reliability of the GIS. The grounding of the GIS is the most important protection against overvoltage stress. The very fast transient overvoltage generated internally within the GIS could become incident on externally connected apparatus.}
}@article{https://doi.org/10.1002/smr.1952,
