abstract = {Summary Power systems are undergoing a massive transformation in recent times, to accommodate a variety of new actors entering this space. The generation sector is getting an unprecedented renewable penetration at different voltage levels that change the status quo of upstream and downstream power flow. The consumption sector is also getting many emerging entrants at medium voltage level, namely charging infrastructure and data centers, that require a lot of power quality adjustments to maintain the stability and grid code compliance, both at source and load end. The transmission and distribution sector thus need to align with the generation and consumption profiles, so that the power flow becomes smooth, seamless, and free from interruptions. All these constraints must be addressed under the ambit of a decarbonized world (grid) while taking a lot of other political and climatic volatilities into consideration. This chapter notes down some of these problems and addresses them with relevant technology innovations, defining the role of smart power systems and making various interplays possible. The effervescence of digitalization in the grid network has been elaborated, with possible integration of AI, data science, communication technology, etc.; which already proved effective in other domains. The concept of a holistic condition monitoring for more systemic interactions and correlation between different assets in a substation is discussed for smart overloading, grid decongestion, capacity readjustments, etc. Some outlooks for power system are outlined that would be crucial for the prosperity of both users and operators of the grid, by economically benefiting from it.}
